"Write root-level `AGENTS.md` for `crates/zeroclaw-api` (in anticipation of "
"extraction)"
msgstr "`crates/zeroclaw-api` のルートに `AGENTS.md` を作成します。このファイルは、このクレートが将来抽出されることを想定して、エージェント（AI アシスタント）がコードベースを理解し、変更を加えるためのガイドラインを提供します。\n\n```markdown\n# AGENTS.md for `crates/zeroclaw-api`\n\n## Overview\n\n`crates/zeroclaw-api` is a Rust crate that provides an API interface for interacting with the Zeroclaw system. This crate is designed to be modular and is anticipated to be extracted into its own repository in the future.\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe primary purpose of this crate is to expose the functionality of the Zeroclaw system through a well-defined API. It serves as the bridge between the core logic of Zeroclaw and external consumers, such as web applications, command-line tools, or other services.\n\n## Structure\n\nThe crate is organized as follows:\n\n- `src/`: Contains the source code for the API.\n  - `lib.rs`: The main entry point for the crate, defining the public API.\n  - `api/`: Contains the implementation of the API endpoints.\n  - `models/`: Contains data structures used in the API.\n  - `utils/`: Contains utility functions and helpers.\n- `tests/`: Contains integration tests for the API.\n- `Cargo.toml`: Defines the dependencies and metadata for the crate.\n\n## Dependencies\n\nThe crate depends on the following:\n\n- `zeroclaw-core`: The core logic of the Zeroclaw system.\n- `serde`: For serialization and deserialization of data.\n- `tokio`: For asynchronous runtime support.\n- `axum`: For building the HTTP API.\n\n## API Endpoints\n\nThe crate exposes the following API endpoints:\n\n- `GET /health`: Returns the health status of the Zeroclaw system.\n- `POST /data`: Submits data to the Zeroclaw system.\n- `GET /data/{id}`: Retrieves data by ID from the Zeroclaw system.\n\n## Testing\n\nTo run the tests, use the following command:\n\n```bash\ncargo test\n```\n\n## Future Extraction\n\nThis crate is anticipated to be extracted into its own repository. When this happens, the following steps should be taken:\n\n1. Create a new repository for the extracted crate.\n2. Move the contents of `crates/zeroclaw-api` to the new repository.\n3. Update the documentation and dependencies as necessary.\n4. Announce the extraction to the community.\n\n## Contributing\n\nContributions to this crate are welcome. Please ensure that your code follows the existing style and includes appropriate tests.\n\n## License\n\nThis crate is licensed under the MIT License. See the `LICENSE` file for details.\n```\n\nThis `AGENTS.md` file provides a clear and concise guide for agents working with the `crates/zeroclaw-api` crate, ensuring that they understand its purpose, structure, and future plans."

